makers.

the project has moved into a second phase and our first RA has moved to a lectureship at Kings. We now have comparative data and models of transport accessibility and segregation for Sao Paulo and for London and this is looking very promising. We had a short article on the BBC Brazil web site about the project</gtr:description><gtr:id>DB00A198-F97F-44D4-B69F-F5C4DBBB2FFD</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal,Economic,Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>56ddc402db39d7.39657862</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Construction,Environment,Retail,Transport</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>We have been at this grant for about 4 months and have already ascertained that the two cities are very different in terms of their transport, density and economic composition. Essentially we think they are more different in accessibility terms than we expected

